The European "Green Deal"
NEW YORK – Europe has done it.
The "Green Pact for Europe" announced by the European Commission is, to date, the first comprehensive sustainable development plan decided upon by a major region of the planet.
It thus becomes a benchmark for the entire world – a guide for the transition toward a prosperous, socially inclusive, and ecologically sustainable economy, a first agenda, for everyone, to achieve this.
Of course, the task facing Europeans is impressive.
Even reading the documents that have just been made public is overwhelming: a flood at first glance of plans, consultations, regulatory frameworks, laws, budgets, and diplomacy, a large number of involved and related topics, ranging from energy to transport, from food to industry.
Its detractors will mock European bureaucracy.
But it is a bureaucracy in the best Weberian sense of the term: it is rational.
The sustainable development goals are clearly stated, the targets are defined based on objectives set to a timeline, and the programs and procedures are adapted to the targets.
Overall, the stated ambition is to achieve "carbon neutrality" (net zero emissions of greenhouse gases) by 2050, to establish a circular economy that puts an end to the destructive pollution caused by plastics and other petrochemical derivatives, pesticides, and toxic waste, to establish a food system "from farm to table," which does not kill people by making them eat products overly processed by industry, nor does it kill the earth with unsustainable agricultural practices.
And the European Commission understands that the method to achieve this must rely on the citizens themselves.
Again, critics will view the announcements of public consultations as mere window dressing.
But go tell President French Emmanuel Macron, who has been confronted for more than a year with demonstrations turning into riots, or Chilean President Sebastián Piñera, whose country suddenly rose up this autumn after a slight increase in metro ticket prices, that these are useless chatter.
Macron and Piñera are both convinced of the necessity of ecological change.
Both have committed to carbon neutrality for their countries by 2050.
And both are desperately trying to figure out how to organize or structure a public consultation, but in hindsight.
American advocates of neoliberalism will once again mock and claim that the "market" will know how to address climate change.
But one only needs to look at today's United States.
If neoliberalism treats the planet as it has treated American infrastructure, we all have reason to be concerned.
Arriving at an airport in the United States means enduring elevators, escalators, broken shuttles, taxis that don't arrive, non-existent rail connections, highways whose lanes are in such poor condition that they cannot be used, replaced by detours.
The reason for these dysfunctions is simple: corruption.
Each American election cycle now costs 8 billion dollars, if not more, and is funded by billionaires, major oil companies, the military-industrial complex, the healthcare industry lobby, and interest groups determined to lower taxes and protect at all costs the status quo.
Market solutions are a farce when politics is subject to all the influences emanating from it, as is the case in the United States.
The European Green Deal shows what a government should be like, and not a government subordinate to corporate interests.
The European Green Deal in fact demonstrates the success of European social democracy (in its operational sense and not strictly partisan).
A mixed economy, which combines markets, the regulatory power of the state, the public sector, and civil society, will pursue a mixed strategy: public goals, public investments in infrastructure, private investments in industrial transformation, research and development missions based on public-private partnerships, and an informed population.
In fact, it is an industrial policy at its most sophisticated level.
(I have recently outlined, in broad terms, what a social-democratic Green New Deal strategy would look like for the United States.)
We have reasons to be optimistic.
The most important point is that the advanced technologies that will enable the creation of an advanced, decarbonized, resource-efficient, and therefore ecologically sustainable economy exist at the commercial or pre-commercial stage.
By combining renewable energy, digital technologies, advanced materials, and collaborative economy in transportation or other infrastructure, we can decarbonize the energy system, shift to a circular economy, and drastically reduce primary resource flows.
But this requires overcoming three major challenges.
The first is to overcome the interests that seek to maintain the status quo.
Major oil companies will have to absorb the losses, but workers in the sector and mining regions should receive compensation in the form of income support, retraining, and other public assistance.
The European plan rightly claims a "just transition."
The second challenge is that of financing.
Europe, as well as other regions of the world, will need to redirect a relatively small portion of its production, from 1% to 2%, towards the green economy, particularly regarding new infrastructure, public markets, research and development, industrial equipment renewal, etc. The financing will come from the private sector, but also from public budgets.
Europe must stand up to ideologues who oppose an increase in EU spending.
Facts must be taken into account.
The last major challenge is diplomatic.
Europe represents about 9.1% of global carbon dioxide emissions, while China's share is 30% and that of the United States is 14%.
Even if Europe manages to implement its Green Deal in its entirety, it will be in vain if other regions of the world do not join it in its fight.
European leaders therefore rightly consider diplomacy to be fundamental to the success of the Green Deal.
Let us take the example of China.
After decades of rapid growth, which eliminated mass poverty, China has become the world's largest CO2 emitter (although its per capita emissions remain half those of the United States).
China alone will determine the future of the global climate.
On one hand, Chinese leaders know that their country is extremely vulnerable to climate change and risks diplomatic isolation if it does not make sufficient efforts to decarbonize; on the other hand, they must face the dangers of the unfortunate cold war launched by America.
Hardliners within the government and Chinese coal lobbies resist decarbonization, especially since Trump rejects it himself, facing pressure from the United States.
European diplomacy can make a difference if it refuses to comply with America's insidious measures to hinder China and instead offers China a positive and unambiguous partnership: working together to establish sustainable infrastructure, development, and technology in Eurasia, within the framework of a Chinese Green Deal comparable to Europe's.
Such a partnership would be of immense benefit for Europe, China, and the dozen Eurasian countries that lie between them, not to mention the world as a whole.
Europe has taken a historic step with its ambitious, mobilizing, and feasible plan.
The Green Deal is a powerful signal of hope in a world of uncertainties and instability.
